  <p class="eyebrow">Google Apps Script &middot; Quotas &middot; 2026 Official Limits</p>

  <h1>Google Apps Script Execution Time Limit 2026 &mdash; Official Quotas for Consumer &amp; Workspace</h1>

  <p class="subtitle">The exact 2026 quota numbers: 6 minutes per execution on consumer accounts, 30 minutes on Workspace. Why Autocrat and Sheets automations hit them — and the structural fix that works at any order volume.</p>

  <p class="meta-line">Updated April 2026 &middot; Google Apps Script &middot; Quotas &middot; Automation Scaling</p>

  <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom:28px;">
    <span class="label">If your automation just stopped mid-run</span>
    <p>You have hit a quota limit. Here is exactly which one and how to fix it &mdash; free, no upgrade required, works at any order volume.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="answer-box" id="quick-answer">
    <p><strong>Quick answer &mdash; the numbers that matter in 2026:</strong> Consumer (free) Google accounts get a <strong>6-minute maximum execution time</strong> per script run and <strong>90 minutes of total daily runtime</strong>. Google Workspace accounts get <strong>30 minutes per execution</strong> and <strong>6 hours of daily runtime</strong>. UrlFetch calls are capped at <strong>20,000 per day</strong> on consumer accounts. These are the hard limits that cannot be increased &mdash; they are why Autocrat, Sheets automations, and document workflows fail at scale.</p>
  </div>

