  <p>If you have ever seen <strong>&ldquo;Service invoked too many times&rdquo;</strong>, <strong>&ldquo;Exceeded maximum execution time&rdquo;</strong>, or <strong>&ldquo;Could not obtain lock&rdquo;</strong>, you already know the symptom. This guide explains the exact numbers behind those errors, when they appear by account type, and what actually works when order or document volume gets serious.</p>

  <div class="callout-warning">
    <span class="label">&#9888; Running Shopify inventory in Google Sheets?</span>
    <p>Shopify Stocky shuts down August 31, 2026. The free replacement &mdash; <a href="/stocky-swap">Stocky Swap</a> &mdash; logs every order to Google Sheets via Make.com, bypassing Apps Script quota limits entirely. Deploys in 4 minutes. Don&apos;t wait until August.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="what-are-quotas">What Are Google Apps Script Quotas?</h2>
  <p>Google Apps Script quotas are hard limits on how much work a script can do. They exist to protect shared infrastructure. Quotas appear across four layers, all applying simultaneously:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>User-level quotas</strong> &mdash; tied to the Google account running the script. Consumer and Workspace accounts have different ceilings.</li>
    <li><strong>Project-level quotas</strong> &mdash; tied to the Apps Script project itself. Concurrent executions are capped here.</li>
    <li><strong>Service quotas</strong> &mdash; Gmail, Sheets, Drive, UrlFetch each have their own daily limit.</li>
    <li><strong>Execution quotas</strong> &mdash; limits on how long a single run can take and how much total runtime is consumed per day.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>These limits <strong>stack independently</strong>. A workflow can be fine on execution time but fail on service call rate &mdash; which is why the same script works for a small operation and breaks as volume rises.</p>

  <h2 id="exact-limits">The Exact Google Apps Script Quota Limits in 2026</h2>
  <p>These are the official limits as of April 2026. Google updates these without announcement, which is why searches for &ldquo;quotas 2026&rdquo; are so common.</p>

  <div class="quota-numbers">
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">6 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Max execution time &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">A single script run on a free Google account is hard-stopped after 6 minutes. Most common cause of incomplete document generation and partial Sheets processing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">30 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Max execution time &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Google Workspace accounts get 30 minutes per execution &mdash; five times more headroom for large batch jobs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">90 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Daily runtime &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Total combined runtime across all executions per day. Once exhausted, all scripts stop until midnight Pacific Time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">6 hrs</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Daily runtime &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Google Workspace accounts get 6 hours of combined daily execution time &mdash; sufficient for most high-volume automation stacks.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">20,000</div>
      <div class="quota-label">UrlFetch calls per day &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Hits this ceiling fast when automations call external APIs on every order &mdash; Shopify webhooks, tracking endpoints, third-party services.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">100,000</div>
      <div class="quota-label">UrlFetch calls per day &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Five times more headroom. Still a per-day hard limit. Burst usage in the first hour can exhaust this before day end.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">250</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Document creates per day &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Autocrat-style workflows that open, fill, and save documents hit this on busy days before afternoon.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">Midnight PT</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Quota reset time</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">All daily quotas reset at midnight Pacific Time &mdash; not your local timezone.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <span class="label">Consumer vs Workspace &mdash; when to upgrade</span>
    <p>The 6-minute vs 30-minute gap is the single biggest reason to upgrade for automation-heavy operations. See the <a href="/blog/when-to-upgrade-free-make-google-workspace">upgrade decision guide</a> for the exact trigger point and cost calculation.</p>
  </div>

