  <h2 id="why-break">Why Quota Limits Break Your Automations</h2>
  <p>Quota failures follow four predictable root causes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Burst processing</strong> &mdash; too many reads, writes, or document operations in one short window.</li>
    <li><strong>Trigger overlap</strong> &mdash; multiple triggers fire before the previous execution finishes.</li>
    <li><strong>Large batch size</strong> &mdash; one job attempts to process more rows than a 6-minute execution can handle.</li>
    <li><strong>Hidden retry loops</strong> &mdash; failed executions trigger automatic retries, accelerating the failure spiral.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="decision-grid">
    <div class="decision-card"><h4>Light use</h4><p>Simple scripts under 100 rows/day usually stay inside quota with basic monitoring.</p></div>
    <div class="decision-card"><h4>Growing use</h4><p>Past a few hundred rows per day, batching and timing become essential.</p></div>
    <div class="decision-card"><h4>High volume</h4><p>When workflow is mission-critical and volume is unpredictable, shared Apps Script limits are the wrong architecture.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="quote">
    <strong>The honest truth:</strong> Apps Script quotas are a capacity problem, not a coding problem. You can reduce the pain &mdash; but you cannot build unlimited scale on top of fixed infrastructure limits.
  </div>

  <h2 id="error-messages">Common Quota Errors and What They Mean</h2>
  <table class="comparison-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Error Message</th><th>Quota Breached</th><th>Immediate Cause</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Service invoked too many times</strong></td><td>Service call rate</td><td>Too many calls to Sheets, Docs, Drive, or Gmail in a short window</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Exceeded maximum execution time</strong></td><td>6-min / 30-min ceiling</td><td>Single run exceeded the limit &mdash; hard-stopped mid-execution</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Could not obtain lock</strong></td><td>Concurrent execution</td><td>Two runs accessed the same resource simultaneously</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Quota exceeded</strong></td><td>Daily service limit</td><td>UrlFetch, document creates, or email sends hit the daily cap</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Daily limit for sending email exceeded</strong></td><td>100/day consumer cap</td><td>Email sends exhausted before end of day</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>For the specific <strong>&ldquo;Service invoked too many times&rdquo;</strong> error, the fix steps differ from other quota errors. See the <a href="/blog/how-to-fix-service-invoked-too-many-times-in-google-apps-script">step-by-step fix guide</a>.</p>

  <p>If your quota errors are tied to <strong>Shopify order volume</strong>, the <a href="/stocky-swap">Stocky Swap free replacement</a> routes every order through Make.com directly to Google Sheets, bypassing Apps Script execution entirely. No quota ceiling, no 6-minute limit. <a href="/stocky-swap">Deploy free in 4 minutes &rarr;</a></p>

  <h2 id="stay-under">How to Stay Under Quotas (6 Steps)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Batch smaller chunks</strong> &mdash; process 50&ndash;100 rows per run instead of everything at once.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduce API calls aggressively</strong> &mdash; cache sheet values at the start using <code>getValues()</code> once, operate in memory, then write back with a single <code>setValues()</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Stagger triggers</strong> &mdash; separate time-based triggers by at least 5&ndash;10 minutes to prevent overlapping executions.</li>
    <li><strong>Persist state with PropertiesService</strong> &mdash; save progress so a timed-out script resumes from where it stopped.</li>
    <li><strong>Add exponential backoff</strong> &mdash; when a service call fails, retry with increasing delays: 1s, 2s, 4s.</li>
    <li><strong>Use LockService deliberately</strong> &mdash; acquire a lock at the start of any execution touching shared data.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout">
    <span class="label">Limit on these approaches</span>
    <p>Batching can take a 100-row workflow to 500 rows. It cannot take 500 to 5,000. At scale, the daily runtime ceiling is the binding constraint &mdash; and no code optimisation changes a 90-minute daily limit.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="autocrat-section" id="autocrat">
    <p class="section-eyebrow">Autocrat &middot; Document Automation &middot; Quota Fix</p>
    <h2>Why Autocrat Hits Quota Limits &mdash; and the Structural Fix</h2>
    <p>Autocrat is quota-intensive because each document generation triggers 5&ndash;8 service calls in sequence: open Drive, read template, create document, write data, convert to PDF, save, optionally send via Gmail. At 30 document service calls per minute (consumer limit), Autocrat reliably processes around 4&ndash;5 documents per minute &mdash; roughly 25&ndash;30 in a single run before the service rate limit triggers.</p>

    <h3>The Four Autocrat Quota Failure Patterns</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Mid-batch timeout</strong> &mdash; a run of 100+ rows hits the 6-minute ceiling. Rows 1&ndash;40 generate correctly; rows 41&ndash;100 are skipped silently.</li>
      <li><strong>Service rate throttling</strong> &mdash; rapid document creation trips &ldquo;Service invoked too many times&rdquo; mid-run.</li>
      <li><strong>Trigger collision</strong> &mdash; high-frequency form submissions cause concurrent executions fighting for the same lock.</li>
      <li><strong>Daily cap exhaustion</strong> &mdash; at 250 document creates per day (consumer limit), a busy day exhausts the allowance before afternoon.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Structural Fix: Move Document Generation Off Apps Script</h3>
    <p>The reliable solution is moving document generation off Google&apos;s shared execution environment into a <strong>dedicated Make.com scenario</strong> that calls the Google Docs API directly via a private HTTP connection.</p>
    <ul>
