  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-wrap">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">What is the Google Apps Script execution time limit in 2026?</p>
      <p class="a">Consumer (free) Google accounts are capped at <strong>6 minutes per execution</strong>. Google Workspace accounts get <strong>30 minutes per execution</strong>. Scripts that exceed the limit are hard-stopped mid-run &mdash; no graceful shutdown.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">What is the daily runtime limit for Google Apps Script in 2026?</p>
      <p class="a">Consumer accounts get <strong>90 minutes of combined runtime per day</strong>. Google Workspace accounts get <strong>6 hours per day</strong>. All quotas reset at midnight Pacific Time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">What is the Google Apps Script UrlFetch daily limit?</p>
      <p class="a">Consumer accounts: <strong>20,000 UrlFetch calls per day</strong>. Google Workspace: <strong>100,000 per day</strong>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">Have Google Apps Script quotas changed for 2026?</p>
      <p class="a">The core limits &mdash; 6-minute consumer execution, 30-minute Workspace, 90-minute daily consumer runtime &mdash; have remained consistent. New failures in 2026 are more likely caused by volume growth than by Google tightening limits.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">Can Google Apps Script quotas be increased?</p>
      <p class="a">No. The limits are fixed at the infrastructure level and cannot be increased by request, payment, or configuration. The only solution is to move the work outside Apps Script execution entirely.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">Why does my script work in the morning but fail in the afternoon?</p>
      <p class="a">This is the clearest sign of a daily quota problem. Your automations are exhausting the 90-minute daily runtime in the first half of the day. The quota resets at midnight Pacific Time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">Why does the same script work one day and fail the next?</p>
      <p class="a">Variable load. A high-volume day hits limits that a quieter day never reached. The script didn&apos;t change &mdash; the pressure on its quota allowance did.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <p class="q">Is Apps Script still useful for automation in 2026?</p>
      <p class="a">Yes &mdash; as a lightweight trigger and orchestration layer for simple spreadsheet actions and low-volume workflows. It becomes a liability when used as the execution engine for mission-critical, high-volume processing.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

